node.text:
Guilty as charged 🙋🏻‍♀️

Yup, I know you do it too.

Let’s talk about the comparison game. Yeah, that little game where you see a post by someone online and instantly feel worse about yourself because you’re not as attractive, creative, dedicated, passionate, insert any other adjective here.

We all know that the realities:
▪️ Social media is a highlight reel
▪️ There’s so much behind the scenes you don’t see
▪️ Everyone is struggling with something

But… it’s still hard not to compare yourself. It’s still hard not to let it get to you. It’s still hard to feel confident when you don’t think you’re enough.

Ultimately, it isn’t a switch you can turn on and off (although that would be great). It’s going to take time to change your perspective and it’s going to take small adjustments to make that happen.

Here are a few things to consider:
▪️ Spend less time on social media during times when you notice the comparison game starting
▪️ Unfollow accounts that make you feel inadequate
▪️ Remind yourself of the things you’re AMAZING at!
▪️ Set realistic goals of personal growth

I promise you are more than enough exactly as you are and your students are lucky to have you 🖤

node.text:
The truth about burnout 🔥❗

Everyone talks about teacher burnout but no one talks about the solution.

Sorry… but “self care” isn’t the answer 🤷🏻‍♀️ (or at least “self care” in the traditional sense of “taking time your yourself” or “me time”)

Does this sound familiar?
▪️ You feel stressed and worn out
▪️ Someone tells you to take care of yourself
▪️ You try to take time for yourself but end up feeling more behind when you do return to work
▪️ You feel stressed out and worn out EVEN FASTER than before
▪️ Rinse and repeat

Yes, it’s important to take time for yourself. But… how do you take time for yourself without feeling like you’re drowning once you return to work?

The answer isn’t simple, but there are steps you can take (and habits you can build… because let’s be honest, these changes don’t take place overnight) to improve your stress and overwhelm BEFORE it results in burnout.

Here are just a few things you can try:
💡 Improve your workflow (how can you be more EFFICIENT with the time you do have?)
💡 Create a clear separation between work and personal time (what boundaries can you set to create this separation?)
💡 Set realistic expectations (what tasks do you need to prioritize vs. what tasks can you let go of because they aren’t a necessity?)

The reality is that these practices are TRUE forms of self care. You’re making needed changes in your life that have a positive impact on your overall wellbeing

Of course, you should still do things you enjoy like exercise, take baths, binge your favorite show, and snuggle with your pets. But keep in mind that no amount of “me time” can improve your overall feelings of burnout if you continue to step into a toxic, stressful environment without making changes at the ROOT of the problem.

True self care means doing the hard work. Breaking the negative habits you’ve formed. Stepping out of your comfort zone and making changes 🎉

node.text:
Don’t make the same mistake I did! 📧

I have a confession: my first year of teaching, my inbox had thousands of emails sitting in it by the end of the year (#oops)

Yup. True story.

Don’t be like me! If your email inbox is already overwhelming, you can fix it!

Here are 5 tips for keeping a clear email inbox:
1️⃣ Create a routine
2️⃣ Use email folders 3️⃣ Respond using templates
4️⃣ Keep your replies short
5️⃣ Unsubscribe from emails

FREE EMAIL TEMPLATES:
🔗 Link in bio ➡️ Freebies
www.pocketfulofprimary.com/freebies

🖤↗️🏳️ Like, share, and save!

Photo by Michelle Emerson on September 02, 2021. May be an image of text that says '2 USE EMAIL FOLDERS Once you have a routine for answering emails, you need to develop system for processing all the emails currently your inbox. Creating email folders allows you to move emails out of your inbox but still gives you access to them in the future. You will need to create an organizational system of folders that fits your needs. 5 IPS FOR KEEPING CLEAR EMAIL INBOX'.

Photo by Michelle Emerson on September 02, 2021. May be an image of text that says '3 RESPOND USING TEMPLATES If you have typed a similar email response more than twice, you need to create a template. Most email service providers (including Gmail, Outlook, and Yahoo) will allow you to save email templates and easily insert them as you compose reply or new message. Templates save you time and allow you to respond faster. 5 TIPS FOR KEEPING CLEAR EMAIL INBOX'.

Photo by Michelle Emerson on September 02, 2021. May be an image of text that says '4 KEEP YOUR REPLIES SHORT No one likes long emails. Keep your replies short. Use bullets. 5 IPS FOR KEEPING A CLEAR EMAIL INBOX'.

You can save yourself time by unsubscribing from these emails. Look at the bottom of the emails for an "nsue" button or directions on how to stop receiving emails in the future. 5 TIPS FOR KEEPING CLEAR EMAIL INBOX'.

node.text:
Hello September 🖤🍂

Who doesn’t love the fresh start that comes with a new month?!

It’s an opportunity to form new habits, refocus your energy, and move one step closer to reaching your goals 🎉

One of my favorite things to do at the start of a new month is brain dump planning session!

Here are my must-dos:
▪️ Create a one-word focus for the month
▪️ Map out important dates
▪️ Write down to-dos that I know about up front
▪️ Make note of anything else that’s on my mind for the month ahead

I love having a single page to encompass all of these elements (plus, it doesn’t hurt to have some calendars in front of me for easy access)! 🗓️

PLANNER DETAILS:
▪️ Digital Planner: @teachingonthedouble (www.teachingonthedouble.com/store)
▪️ App: Goodnotes
▪️ Stylus: Apple Pencil

P.S. This planner is currently on SALE through tonight! 🎉 This is the last sale for this planner launch.

node.text:
Teaching shouldn’t consume your entire identity 🍎

“Teacher” is just one hat you wear (and you’ve got plenty more in your closet).

You should never let your job as a teacher overshadow those other aspects of who you are as a PERSON.

You can be a teacher AND still be an amazing friend/significant other.
You can be a teacher AND still be a bad-a** athlete.
You can be a teacher AND still run your own business.

You don’t have to choose one passion and give up the rest. You can be multi-faceted and have multiple interests.

For the longest time, I felt guilty leaving school at the end of my contract hours to go to the gym. I felt like if I wasn’t giving my students 100% of my time and energy, I was letting them down.

The complete opposite is true.

I am a better teacher when I explore and pour into my other passions. 

& I’d be willing to bet that you are too 🖤

node.text:
NEW GOOGLE DOCS FEATURE! ✅

Google Docs now let you add a checklist (which you can click to check/cross out and uncheck)!

I love using checkboxes in Google Sheets and my mind is already racing with ideas of how to use them in Google Docs (they still aren’t available in Google Slides but fingers crossed they will come soon…. right, @Google?)

How to insert the checklist (2 ways):
▪️ Find the checklist icon next to the bulleted list in the toolbar (swipe to see)
▪️Click “Format”, “Bullets & numbering”, and then “Checklist”

Ideas for using the checklist:
💡 Checklist for students of tasks to complete within an assignment or project
💡 To-do list after a meeting
💡 To-do list when collaborative team planning

I can’t wait to hear YOUR ideas for how you could use this new feature! Leave a comment below with your thoughts! 👇🏻

node.text:
Do you always include a “Meet the Teacher” letter for families during back to school? 🍎

A “Meet the Teacher” letter is a great way to introduce yourself to families and set the tone for collaboration between the teacher and families for the year!

Here’s some of my favorite things to include in the letter:
▪️How to pronounce your name (especially if it isn’t clear)
▪️Information about your education and/or certifications
▪️Contact information (including your preferred method of contact)
▪️Some of your favorite things (color, food, etc.)
▪️Your excitement for the year ahead

If you haven’t created your “Meet the Teacher” letter yet, I can help you out!

I’ve got a set of templates for your letter that are already formatted so all you have to do is add your personal information!

It even includes my old Meet the Teacher letter as an example because I KNOW how much having an example can help! 🎉

You can grab the templates here:
bit.ly/meettheteacherlettertemplates

node.text:
It’s been one of “those” days 🥰

Do you ever just get into a creative flow and feel more YOU than you have in a long time?

You come up with one idea (and finally write it down because otherwise you’ll lose it) and then your brain just explodes with creativity. Before you know it, your one idea has expanded into an entire family of little ideas that all connect together and you feel so much pride for your creations.

Maybe it’s a lesson or unit or transformation or anchor chart or something in-between but it feels really, really good.

You feel confident in yourself, your abilities, and your ideas 💡

Maybe it’s the fact that I cleaned the entire house today or maybe it’s the multiple cups of coffee I’ve consumed… but I can’t WAIT to share these ideas with you all 🎉

Here’s to hoping that you had one of those days, or you have one soon because they are beyond refreshing for the soul 🖤

Exciting news and a FREEBIE for you! 🎉

Google Keep is an incredible FREE website and app that works like virtual sticky notes… you can store text, images, create checklists, and MORE! 💻

Google Keep is a great way to store important links, recurring checklists, meeting notes, and everything in-between 🥰

I’ve got a set of my favorite headers for Google Keep that I’m giving them to you for FREE! You can grab them on my website at www.pocketfulofprimary.com/freebies (or use the link in my profile).

I’ve had TONS of requests for an editable set of headers so you can customize them to fit your needs and they are finally ready! 🎉

My EDITABLE Google Keep Headers include 60 different images (in both black and white) with editable text and backgrounds! The number of headers you could create is ENDLESS!

You can grab the editable headers here:
bit.ly/googlekeepheaderseditable

If you aren’t sure exactly how to create the headers or insert them on Google Keep, I’ve got you covered! The product includes a multi-page guide with ideas for using Google Keep and directions for inserting the headers! 💻
